* Last but not least, in `TaskAspect` you use `@annotation(com.spring.aspect.interfaces.annotation.Task)` which would match methods with a `@Task` annotation. But you have classes with that annotation, so you ought to use `@within(com.spring.aspect.interfaces.annotation.Task)` instead.

* Even easier than trying to bind the `Task` annotation to an argument via `target(task)` would be to just use `@within(task)` instead, getting you both the annotation matching and the parameter binding at once.

* Remember we changed the task pointcuts from `@Around` to `@Before` above? For `@Before` AspectJ does not generate methods but weaves the code directly into the target classes. You also cannot rely on it to do that for `@Around` advices, so my answer to your previous question was working but a bit unclean. There is a special pointcut designator `adviceexecution()`, though. Its purpose is to intercept executing advices from other aspects (or even from the same one). This is cleaner and more generic. In this case it is even the only thing that works.

* Finally, you are using `args(proceedingJoinPoint)`, I have no idea why. Did you try to bind the pointcut from the intercepted `Task{1,2,3}` advices to the `TaskAspect` advice? It would not work that way because AspectJ binds the executing advice&#39;s joinpoint to an existing first parameter of type `JoinPoint` or `ProceedingJoinPoint`. Maybe it would work binding it to a second joinpoint parameter. Anyway, we don&#39;t need it, so let us just remove it. This is really contrived, wow.

* One more thing, why are you using `task.getClass().getName()` instead of your newly introduced `@Task` annotation properties in order to log information?

&lt;!-- language: java --&gt;

    package com.spring.aspect.interfaces.aspect;
    
