In JavaScript, the months starts from 0 if not supplied as a date string.

For example, `new Date(2019,0,1)` will return _Jan 1, 2019_ and `new Date(2019,1,1)` will return _Feb 1, 2019_

At the same time, `new Date(&quot;2019/1/1&quot;)` will return _Jan 1, 2019_

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    console.log(new Date(2019,0,1).toString())
    console.log(new Date(2019,1,1).toString())


&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

In your code, it calculates the difference between _Oct 24, 2019_ and _Nov 1, 2019_. October have 31 days hence 8 is the right answer. To get the difference for _Sep 24, 2019_ and _Oct 1, 2019_, you need to reduce 1 from the value of month.

You need to correct your code to the following

    date1 = new Date(date1[2], parseInt(date1[0])-1, date1[1]);
    date2 = new Date(date2[2], parseInt(date2[0])-1, date2[1]);

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function DaysBetween(str1, str2) {
      var date1 = str1;
      var date2 = str2;
      date1 = date1.split(&quot;/&quot;);
      date2 = date2.split(&quot;/&quot;);
      var oneday = 24 * 60 * 60 * 1e3;
      date1 = new Date(date1[2], parseInt(date1[0]) - 1, date1[1]);
      date2 = new Date(date2[2], parseInt(date2[0]) - 1, date2[1]);
      var diffDays = Math.round(Math.abs((date1.getTime() - date2.getTime()) / oneday));
      if (diffDays == 0) {
        diffDays = 1;
      }

      console.log(diffDays);
      return diffDays;
    }
    DaysBetween(&quot;9/24/2019&quot;, &quot;10/1/2019&quot;);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


And here&#39;s a suggestion. You don&#39;t need all these lines. This can be easily done by the following code

    function dateDiff(d1,d2){
      return (new Date(d2).getTime() - new Date(d1).getTime())/(1000 * 60 * 60 * 24);
    }

Which will get the time in unix timestamp, find difference and then divide it by _1000 * 60 * 60 * 24_ to find days.


&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function dateDiff(d1,d2){
      return (new Date(d2).getTime() - new Date(d1).getTime())/(1000 * 60 * 60 * 24);
    }

    console.log(dateDiff(&quot;2019/9/24&quot;,&quot;2019/10/1&quot;));

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

 A true Date object, in many languages, is a numeric representation of time from some Epoch value. Javascript uses the number of milliseconds since the Unix Epoch of 1 January 1970, Midnight. So to find the difference between two dates, it can be simple math: 

_For d1 = &#39;2020-01-01&#39; and d2 = &#39;2021-01-01&#39;_

    new Date(d2) - new Date(d1)

Which will give you a number of milliseconds difference between the two dates. If you want, you can check if `d1` is less than `d2` or whatever, or you can just set the absolute value to get the difference, regardless of which one is greater. Note that this does not take a `time` element into consideration. If you want to factor for that, there are a couple of more steps. 

But now that we&#39;ve got a difference in milliseconds, we need to convert that to days. 

There are 86,400,000 milliseconds in one day, so we can just divide our value by that to get days. 

    (new Date(d2) - new Date(d1))/86400000

But that will potentially give us a decimal number. So we need to get rid of that. `Math` to the rescue again.

    Math.floor( Math.abs((new Date(d2) - new Date(d1)))/86400000 )

Then we make this all into a function so we can reuse it. 

    function getDaysBetween(d1,d2){
      return ( Math.floor( Math.abs((new Date(d2) - new Date(d1)))/86400000 ) ) ;
    }


So `console.log( getDaysDiff(&#39;2020-01-01&#39;,&#39;2021-01-01&#39;) ) ;` will give us `366`. Javascript `Date` object does take into account Leap Days, but it doesn&#39;t account for Leap Seconds. If that&#39;s a concern, you&#39;ll have to account for it. Also note that if you are taking care of dates from different time zones, you may have to account for that also. My function above only calculates for full days difference. So if you have two dates from two timezones (1 Jan 2019 0100 EST and 2 Jan 2019 0100 PST), you may want to account correctly for timezone differences.

Also, I&#39;m not doing any error checking to validate you pass the function a valid date. If it&#39;s invalid, you&#39;ll get a `NaN` result.



&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function getDaysBetween(d1,d2){
      return ( Math.floor( Math.abs((new Date(d2) - new Date(d1)))/86400000 ) ) ;
    }
    
    console.log( getDaysBetween(&#39;2020-01-01&#39;,&#39;2021-01-01&#39;) ) ;
    
    
    d1 = &#39;09/24/2019&#39; ;
    d2 = &#39;09/30/2019&#39; ;
    d3 = &#39;10/01/2019&#39; ;
    
    console.log(getDaysBetween(d1,d2)); //6
    console.log(getDaysBetween(d1,d3)); //7

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;



